@Bill - in my Catholic high school, track 1 (college-bound) students were required three years of Latin and two of a modern language (I did four of both). On day 1 of first-year Latin we were assigned at random a sentence as a motto. By the end of year one, we had to cite the author and origin, give a brief biography of the author and a précis of the source matter, say it in both classical and ecclesiastical style, parse it, translate it, and explain what it had come to mean for us. (I had an excellent Latin teacher that year.) Sadly, such an exercise is rendered meaningless now, as one could show the printed phrase to the camera on a smart phone and let the internet do the rest.

“Medio (in via) tutissimus ibis” was mine. “In the middle course you shall go most safely,” from Ovid’s Metamorphoses II: advice (sadly ignored) given to Icarus by Daedalus.

My Latin teacher was fired the next year for teaching too much Ovid and not enough of the war-mongering Caesar and friends.

@Linda

Ah, is that what it refers to? I'd never actually heard of it. From google/Wikipedia it seems "a la meunière" translates to "in the style of the miller's wife" "from molinarius, a miller", not actually deriving from "menu", but still it seems that's likely what the clue was going for.

The description of sole meunière tells.me it's a fish dish with about everything I love about ways to serve fish (though not the only way I enjoy fish). Battered, fried, butterbutter, lemon lemon lemon, and something green. Even without my fav addition, garlic, it sounds wonderful.

